Amid this feverish anxiety and oppressive anguish, 3 when I was without a breath of any plan, lo ! our holy son Pinianus suddenly and unexpectedly sends a servant of God to me to tell me that he wanted him to swear to the people that, if he were ordained against his will, he would leave Africa altogether3 his notion was, I imagine, that seeing he could not break his oath‚ they would not go on clamouring with such persistence, if it only resulted in driving from the country a man whom we ought at least to have as a neighbour. But since it appeared to me that we had to sear a more violent outburst of resentment from them in consequence of an oath of this kind, I kept it to myself and said nothing about it3 and as he had asked at the same time that I should go to him, I went at once. After telling me the same thing, he immediately added to that oath a point. that he had sent another servant of God to put to me while I was on my way to him, namely, about his residence in Hippo, provided that no one compelled him to undertake the burden of clerical office against his will. At such an impasse, this refreshed me like a breath of air, but I said nothing to him and went with hurried step to brother Alypius and told him what he had said. But he,seeking, I think, to avoid responsibility for any occurrence that he thought might give you offence, made answer, “ Let no one ask my advice about it.'' On hearing this, I returned
